const content = `<p><strong>PPC services</strong> — pay-per-click advertising management — cover everything required to run paid search campaigns that generate qualified inbound leads: keyword research, ad creation, bid management, audience targeting, landing page strategy, call tracking, and ongoing campaign optimisation. For home service contractors, a well-run PPC program means the phone rings with people who have a real job, not tire-kickers shopping for prices. Done right, it's one of the most controllable and measurable ways to fill your schedule. Done wrong, it burns through budget fast with little to show for it.</p>

<h2>What PPC Services Actually Include</h2>

<p>Most contractors have heard the term but don't know exactly what they're paying for when they sign on with a PPC agency. Here's a breakdown of what a proper PPC service engagement covers — and what separates a real program from one that looks good on paper but underdelivers in the field.</p>

<h3>Campaign Strategy and Account Structure</h3>

<p>Before a single ad goes live, the campaign needs a structure that matches how homeowners actually search. That means separating campaigns by service type — HVAC installation, AC repair, furnace replacement — rather than lumping everything into one catch-all campaign. It means deciding which services get dedicated budget, which markets to target first, and what match types to use on keywords.</p>

<p>This is where most low-cost PPC setups fall apart. A generic campaign structure treating "plumbing services" the same as "emergency burst pipe repair" will waste money on broad, unqualified traffic. Good campaign architecture is invisible when it works, expensive when it's missing.</p>

<h3>Keyword Research and Negative Keyword Management</h3>

<p>Keyword research for home services isn't just finding high-volume terms. It's identifying the specific search phrases homeowners use when they're ready to call — not when they're researching options or reading DIY articles. Phrases like "HVAC repair near me" or "emergency plumber [city]" have strong commercial intent. "How does a furnace work" does not.</p>

<p>Negative keywords are equally important. Without a thorough negative keyword list, your ads show up for searches like "DIY roof repair," "roofing jobs hiring," or competitor brand names — clicks you pay for that will never convert. Building and maintaining a negative keyword list is ongoing work, not a one-time task.</p>

<h3>Ad Copy and Creative Testing</h3>

<p>Ad copy for home service companies needs to do one thing well: get the right person to call. That means leading with the service, the location, and a reason to act now — not generic branding language. Ads that include specific trust signals (licensed, insured, same-day service, free estimates) consistently outperform vague ads that just say "quality service."</p>

<p>A good PPC service includes ongoing A/B testing of headlines and descriptions to find what resonates with your specific market. Google's responsive search ads allow multiple headline and description combinations — managing these actively versus setting them and forgetting them makes a measurable difference in click-through rates and lead quality.</p>

<h3>Landing Page Strategy and Conversion Optimisation</h3>

<p>A click that doesn't convert to a call or form submission is wasted spend. Sending paid traffic to a generic homepage — instead of a dedicated service page or landing page — is one of the most common reasons PPC campaigns underperform for contractors.</p>

<p>Effective PPC services include guidance (and often management) of landing page content, layout, and conversion elements: clear headline, specific service description, trust signals, prominent phone number, simple form, and fast load speed. On mobile, where the majority of home service searches happen, this matters even more. A landing page that loads slowly or buries the phone number will drop your conversion rate regardless of how well the ads are performing.</p>

<h3>Bid Management and Budget Allocation</h3>

<p>Google Ads bidding isn't set-and-forget. Bids need to be adjusted based on time of day, day of week, device type, geographic location, and campaign performance data. For home service companies, calls made during business hours are worth more — your team can answer them. Calls at 2am generate voicemails that often go cold.</p>

<p>Smart bid management also means shifting budget toward your highest-converting services and pulling back on campaigns that are generating clicks but not booked jobs. This requires someone watching the data and making adjustments weekly — not just pulling a monthly report.</p>

<h3>Call Tracking and Attribution</h3>

<p>If you can't tell which campaigns are generating calls and which are generating nothing, you can't make smart decisions about where to spend. Call tracking assigns unique phone numbers to each campaign or ad group, so you know exactly which searches led to a call, which calls turned into bookings, and what the real cost-per-lead is by service type.</p>

<p>This data is what separates a campaign you can improve from one you're just maintaining. Form submission tracking works the same way — every lead source should be tagged so the attribution is accurate, not estimated.</p>

<h2>Google Ads vs. Local Services Ads: How They Fit Together</h2>

<table>
  <thead>
    <tr>
      <th>Feature</th>
      <th>Google Ads (Search)</th>
      <th>Local Services Ads (LSAs)</th>
    </tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td>Position on page</td>
      <td>Below LSAs, above organic results</td>
      <td>Top of search results</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>How you pay</td>
      <td>Per click</td>
      <td>Per lead (call or message)</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Google Guaranteed badge</td>
      <td>No</td>
      <td>Yes</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Control over targeting</td>
      <td>High — keywords, audiences, bids</td>
      <td>Limited — service type and area</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Lead quality control</td>
      <td>Managed through targeting and copy</td>
      <td>Can dispute invalid leads</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Best for</td>
      <td>Specific services, competitive terms, volume</td>
      <td>Brand trust, top-of-page presence, lower CPL</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<p>Most established home service contractors benefit from running both. LSAs provide top-of-page visibility and a trust badge that increases call rates. Google Ads give you control over which services you advertise, which search terms trigger your ads, and how aggressively you compete for specific high-value jobs. Running them together creates more coverage at the top of search results and improves your overall cost-per-booked-job compared to relying on either alone.</p>

<h2>What Separates a PPC Service That Generates Leads from One That Just Generates Clicks</h2>

<p>Clicks are easy to buy. Qualified calls from homeowners ready to book a job are harder to generate — and that distinction is where most PPC programs either earn their fee or fall short.</p>

<p>The common failure patterns are predictable:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Broad match keywords without controls</strong> — ads show up for searches that have nothing to do with your services, spend burns fast, lead quality is poor</li>
  <li><strong>Generic landing pages</strong> — traffic lands on a homepage with no clear action, no service specificity, and a phone number buried in the footer</li>
  <li><strong>No negative keyword maintenance</strong> — the same irrelevant searches keep triggering ads month after month</li>
  <li><strong>Set-and-forget bid strategies</strong> — bids don't reflect seasonal demand, time-of-day patterns, or which services are actually converting</li>
  <li><strong>No call tracking</strong> — the agency reports on clicks and impressions, but no one actually knows how many calls came in or what they cost</li>
  <li><strong>Single campaign for all services</strong> — a plumbing company's drain cleaning ads compete for the same budget as their water heater replacement ads, with no separation by value or intent</li>
</ul>

<p>Each of these issues individually will drag down performance. When several stack on top of each other — which they often do in generic agency setups — the result is a campaign that looks active on a dashboard but isn't generating real work.</p>

<h2>What Contractors Should Expect to Spend on PPC</h2>

<p>PPC costs for home service companies have two components: the management fee and the actual ad spend. These are separate, and both matter.</p>

<p><strong>Management fees</strong> typically run $1,000–$3,500/month depending on the scope of campaigns, number of services managed, and what's included (LSA management, landing page work, reporting, call tracking setup). Be cautious of agencies that charge a percentage of ad spend as their primary fee structure — it creates an incentive to increase your budget regardless of performance.</p>

<p><strong>Ad spend</strong> varies significantly by market and trade. In a mid-size market, most home service contractors spend $2,000–$5,000/month on Google Ads. In highly competitive metros — major cities, dense suburban markets — roofing and HVAC companies routinely spend $5,000–$15,000/month. The benchmark to track isn't how much you're spending, it's your cost-per-booked-job. A campaign spending $8,000/month that books 20 jobs at $400/job is a better result than one spending $4,000/month that books 6 jobs at $667/job.</p>

<h2>How to Evaluate a PPC Service Before You Commit</h2>

<p>If you've been burned by an agency before — or you're comparing options now — these are the questions worth asking:</p>

<ol>
  <li><strong>Do you work specifically with home service companies?</strong> A generalist agency managing retail, SaaS, and contractor campaigns simultaneously doesn't have the same depth of knowledge on how homeowners search, what drives calls, or how seasonal demand affects bidding.</li>
  <li><strong>How do you structure campaigns by service type?</strong> If the answer is vague, that's a red flag. A contractor serving five different services needs five campaign structures, not one.</li>
  <li><strong>What does your call tracking setup look like?</strong> If they can't explain exactly how they attribute calls back to specific campaigns and keywords, your reporting will be guesswork.</li>
  <li><strong>What do you report on, and how often?</strong> Impressions and clicks are vanity metrics. You want to see cost-per-lead, call volume, conversion rates, and — if possible — cost-per-booked-job.</li>
  <li><strong>Who manages the account day-to-day?</strong> Some agencies sell at the senior level and hand off to a junior coordinator. Know who's actually in your account and how much attention it gets.</li>
</ol>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

<h3>What are PPC services for home service companies?</h3>
<p>PPC services for home service companies cover the full setup and management of paid search campaigns — primarily Google Ads and Local Services Ads. This includes keyword research, ad creation, bid management, landing page strategy, and ongoing optimisation to generate qualified calls and form submissions from homeowners ready to book.</p>

<h3>How much do PPC services cost for contractors?</h3>
<p>Most home service contractors spend $1,500–$4,000/month on PPC management fees, plus their actual ad spend budget. Ad spend varies widely by market and trade — HVAC and roofing companies in competitive metros often spend $3,000–$10,000/month on ads alone. A good agency will help you understand cost-per-lead benchmarks before you commit.</p>

<h3>What's the difference between Google Ads and Local Services Ads?</h3>
<p>Google Ads are traditional paid search ads where you bid on keywords and pay per click. Local Services Ads appear above Google Ads and charge per lead, not per click. LSAs also display a Google Guaranteed badge, which increases trust with homeowners. Most contractors benefit from running both together for stronger top-of-page coverage.</p>

<h3>How long does it take for PPC to generate leads?</h3>
<p>Google Ads can generate leads within days of launch. However, meaningful performance data — enough to make smart optimisation decisions — typically takes 30–60 days. LSAs often take 2–4 weeks to gain traction as Google's algorithm learns your service area and job types. Expect a ramp-up period before results stabilise.</p>

<h3>What makes a PPC campaign generate quality leads vs. junk leads?</h3>
<p>Lead quality comes down to targeting precision. Campaigns using tight keyword match types, specific service-area targeting, thorough negative keyword lists, and conversion-focused landing pages consistently generate better leads. Broad match keywords and generic ad copy attract clicks from people who aren't ready to book — driving up cost without increasing booked jobs.</p>

<h3>Should a home service company manage their own PPC or hire an agency?</h3>
<p>Managing PPC in-house is possible, but it requires time, platform expertise, and ongoing attention most contractors don't have. Poorly managed campaigns routinely waste 30–50% of ad spend on irrelevant clicks. A specialist focused on home services will typically deliver better lead quality and a lower cost-per-booked-job than a generalist agency or a DIY setup.</p>

<h2>Ready to Find Out Where Your PPC Budget Is Actually Going?</h2>

<p>If your current campaigns are generating clicks but not consistent calls — or you're not sure whether your ad spend is producing real booked jobs — Thomas Town Digital offers free audits for home service contractors. We'll go through your account structure, keyword targeting, landing pages, and call tracking to show you exactly what's working, what's wasted, and where the real opportunity is. Book a free 15-minute strategy call at <strong>thomastowndigital.com</strong> and walk away with a clear picture of what your PPC should be doing for your business.</p>`;

